{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476282"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.15,0.14,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1967"},{"type":"tags","id":"2042"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43914"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old infant presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a history of persistent jaundice since birth. The parent reports pale stools and dark urine. The infant has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the infant appears well with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure of 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate of 30/min, SpO2 of 98%, and temperature of 36.8\u00b0C. The abdomen is soft but there is hepatomegaly. Blood tests reveal conjugated bilirubin levels of 120 \u03bcmol/L (\u0026lt;20) and liver enzymes with ALT 150 U/L (\u0026lt;50) and ALP 600 U/L (110-320).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start phototherapy","Refer for liver biopsy","Initiate ursodeoxycholic acid","Refer for Kasai portoenterostomy","Schedule for liver transplant"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of persistent jaundice since birth, pale stools, dark urine, hepatomegaly, and elevated conjugated bilirubin and liver enzymes is highly suggestive of biliary atresia. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erefer for Kasai portoenterostomy\u003C/strong\u003E. This surgical procedure aims to restore bile flow and prevent further liver damage. It should be performed as early as possible, ideally within the first two to three months of life, to improve outcomes. The procedure involves resecting all the extra hepatic bile duct remnants and bringing up a Roux limb of small bowel to anastomose to the hepatic parenchyma surrounding the area of bile duct resections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhototherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia, typically seen in physiological jaundice or haemolytic conditions. It is not effective for conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia, which is characteristic of biliary atresia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can help confirm the diagnosis of biliary atresia and rule out other causes of neonatal cholestasis. However, it should not delay the referral for Kasai portoenterostomy, as early intervention is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrsodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is used to manage other cholestatic liver diseases by promoting bile flow and reducing liver inflammation. While it may be used as an adjunctive therapy in biliary atresia, it is not the primary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver transplant\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if the Kasai procedure fails or if there is significant liver damage. However, it is not the initial step in management and is typically considered after exhausting other treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early surgical intervention is crucial in the management of biliary atresia to prevent liver damage and improve outcomes."],"references":["Brumbaugh D, Mack C. Conjugated hyperbilirubinemia in children. Pediatr Rev. 2012;33(7):291-302. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22753787/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T17:56:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T17:56:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"item